Acquire Volatile Memory with DumpIt & LiME
Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Acquire volatile memory from Windows and Linux systems using DumpIt and LiME
Set up and execute memory acquisition tools on a single Linux machine
Analyze memory dumps to identify system artifacts and evidence
Understand the importance of volatile memory in digital forensics
Prerequisites
Basic Linux command-line knowledge
Understanding of file systems and directory navigation
Familiarity with compilation processes (make, gcc)
Root/sudo access on the target system
Lab Environment
Al Nafi provides Linux-based cloud machines for this lab. Simply click Start Lab to access your dedicated bare metal Linux machine. No pre-installed tools are provided, so you will install all required software during the lab exercises.

Task 1: Set up and Run DumpIt for Windows Memory Acquisition
Subtask 1.1: Install Wine for Windows Compatibility
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y wine winetricks
Subtask 1.2: Download and Configure DumpIt
# Create working directory
mkdir ~/memory-lab
cd ~/memory-lab

# Download DumpIt (using wget with a sample URL - replace with actual source)
wget -O dumpit.exe "https://download.moonsols.com/application/files/3815/8737/3441/DumpIt.exe"

# Make executable
chmod +x dumpit.exe
Subtask 1.3: Create Test Windows Environment
# Initialize Wine prefix
winecfg

# Create a sample memory scenario
wine cmd /c "echo Creating test environment for memory acquisition"
Subtask 1.4: Execute DumpIt Memory Acquisition
# Run DumpIt through Wine
wine dumpit.exe

# Alternative command-line execution
wine dumpit.exe /output memory_dump.dmp /quiet
Subtask 1.5: Verify Windows Memory Dump
# Check dump file creation
ls -lh *.dmp

# Display basic file information
file memory_dump.dmp
hexdump -C memory_dump.dmp | head -20
Task 2: Use LiME for Linux Memory Acquisition
Subtask 2.1: Install Development Dependencies
sudo apt install -y build-essential linux-headers-$(uname -r) git
Subtask 2.2: Download and Compile LiME
# Clone LiME repository
git clone https://github.com/504ensicsLabs/LiME.git
cd LiME/src

# Compile LiME kernel module
make
Subtask 2.3: Load LiME Module and Acquire Memory
# Load the kernel module and create memory dump
sudo insmod lime-$(uname -r).ko "path=../linux_memory.lime format=lime"

# Verify module loaded
lsmod | grep lime

# Check dump file creation
ls -lh ../linux_memory.lime
Subtask 2.4: Alternative LiME Acquisition Methods
# Raw format acquisition
sudo insmod lime-$(uname -r).ko "path=../linux_memory_raw.dd format=raw"

# Network-based acquisition (TCP)
sudo insmod lime-$(uname -r).ko "path=tcp:4444 format=lime"
Subtask 2.5: Unload LiME Module
# Remove the kernel module
sudo rmmod lime

# Verify removal
lsmod | grep lime
Task 3: Analyze Memory Dumps for Artifacts
Subtask 3.1: Install Volatility Framework
# Install Python and pip
sudo apt install -y python3 python3-pip

# Install Volatility3
pip3 install volatility3

# Verify installation
vol3 --help
Subtask 3.2: Analyze Linux Memory Dump
# Move to LiME directory
cd ~/memory-lab/LiME

# Basic system information
vol3 -f linux_memory.lime linux.info

# List running processes
vol3 -f linux_memory.lime linux.pslist

# Show network connections
vol3 -f linux_memory.lime linux.netstat
Subtask 3.3: Extract Process Information
# Process tree view
vol3 -f linux_memory.lime linux.pstree

# Command line arguments
vol3 -f linux_memory.lime linux.cmdline

# Open files by processes
vol3 -f linux_memory.lime linux.lsof
Subtask 3.4: Memory Strings Analysis
# Extract strings from memory dump
strings linux_memory.lime > memory_strings.txt

# Search for specific patterns
grep -i "password" memory_strings.txt
grep -i "http" memory_strings.txt | head -10
grep -E "[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}" memory_strings.txt | head -10
Subtask 3.5: Compare Memory Acquisition Methods
# Compare file sizes
ls -lh linux_memory.lime linux_memory_raw.dd

# Basic file analysis
file linux_memory.lime
file linux_memory_raw.dd

# Create comparison report
echo "Memory Acquisition Comparison Report" > analysis_report.txt
echo "====================================" >> analysis_report.txt
echo "LiME Format Size: $(ls -lh linux_memory.lime | awk '{print $5}')" >> analysis_report.txt
echo "Raw Format Size: $(ls -lh linux_memory_raw.dd | awk '{print $5}')" >> analysis_report.txt
echo "Acquisition Time: $(date)" >> analysis_report.txt
Subtask 3.6: Create Memory Timeline
# Generate timeline from memory
vol3 -f linux_memory.lime linux.pslist --output-file process_timeline.csv

# Display timeline summary
head -20 process_timeline.csv
